[The posting's 1st reference (Olesen B, Jensen C, Olsen K, Fussing V, Gerner-Smidt P, Scheutz F: VTEC O117:K1:H7. A new clonal group of E. coli associated with persistent diarrhoea in Danish travellers. Scand J Infect Dis. 2005;37:288-94) has its abstract shown below:

"20 patients were infected with a new group of verocytotoxin-producing _E. coli_ (VTEC) strains of serotype O117:K1:H7 during a 5-y period. The main symptoms were persistent watery diarrhea with abdominal cramps; 2 persons of the 20 were healthy carriers. The duration of gastrointestinal symptoms in patients was median 11 weeks with 80 percent being ill for more than 30 d. In 19 cases the infection was acquired during travel (Asia, Africa and Cuba), and 1 case was laboratory acquired. All strains were positive for the vtx1 gene and negative for the vtx2, the eae, the saa and the ehxA genes. 13 strains (65 percent) were resistant to 4 or more antimicrobial agents. By PFGE using the restriction enzyme XbaI, the strains were clonally related, but not identical. O117:K1:H7 is a clonal group of VTEC that should be considered in patients returning from Africa and Asia with long-lasting watery diarrhea."

The absence of the intimin gene (eae) does not necessarily mean that complications related to Shiga toxin cannot occur. Readers should recall the quite large outbreak, centered in northern Germany, of the chimeric _E. coli_ O104:H4 which was Shiga toxin positive without eae and contained genetic information from enteroaggregative _E. coli_ as well. This outbreak was associated with a large number of deaths associated with hemolytic uremic syndrome and associated renal failure as well as central nervous system complications (1,2). This organism (O117:H7) does not seem to do this but causes more chronic watery diarrhea. Although the posting implies that it can be confused with _Shigella sonnei_, the disease complex associated with shigellosis is a dysentery with bloody, mucous containing diarrhea and fever. EHEC almost never causes fever or frank dysentery.

References:
1. Buchholz U, Bernard H, Werber D, et al: German outbreak of _Escherichia coli_ O104:H4 associated with sprouts. N Engl J Med. 2011; 365: 1763-70.
2. Frank C, Werber D, Cramer JP, et al: Epidemic profile of Shiga-toxin-producing _Escherichia coli_ O104:H4 outbreak in Germany. N Engl J Med. 2011; 365: 1771-80.
- Mod.LL

